	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Providence</placeName> <date>July 28<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1856</date>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><placeName>Phila</placeName></p>	
			<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>	
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear &#38; rev. Sir&#33;</p>
				<p>I take the liberty to <sic>adress</sic> a<lb/> few lines to you again but<lb/> first of all let me thank you<lb/> for your kind letter and valuable<lb/> advice which you <sic>was</sic> kind enough<lb/> to address to me.  The object<lb/> of this here my letter is for<lb/> a different one&#44; but at the same<lb/> time very important.</p>
				<p>In our city here lives a man<lb/> who is a &#8222;<hi rend="underline">Meshumcth</hi>&#8221;<lb/>  He is in Thorah and Talmud<lb/> very well versed&#44; having been a<lb/> teacher in <placeName>Kracow</placeName>&#44; but when<lb/> about 17&#95;18 years old he was<lb/> persuaded by an English Missionary<lb/> to commit that fatal crime to<lb/> desert his religion.  But now<lb/> he is really repentant of it and<lb/> wants to become again<lb/> a &#8222;member of <placeName>Israel</placeName>.&#8221;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>The man is a cigar maker here<lb/> and makes a living but has not<lb/> funds enough to go to <placeName>N. York</placeName> for<lb/> some time to accomplish his object<lb/> neither has he friends or acquaintances<lb/> there to help him&#44; but now my<lb/> dear isr&#44; what shall we do to<lb/> assist him and in fact what is<lb/> necessary for us to do in regard<lb/> to him.  We are all <hi rend="underline">young</hi> and<lb/> <hi rend="underline">inexperienced</hi> mautheraud<add>&#63;</add> truly<lb/> need the guidance and <sic>advises</sic><lb/> of such a man as you sometimes.<lb/>  We do not know much about<lb/> our religion&#44; all we know is we<lb/> were born Jehudim and want to<lb/> die as such&#44; following the <hi rend="underline">old</hi> Belief<lb/> of our fathers <del>wh</del> without making<lb/> additional safety wolves on&#44; to the<lb/> old Religion&#44; in order to suit<lb/> our convenience better&#44; than our God&#44;<lb/> as some of the Reformers do.<lb/>  But guidance we need once and<lb/> a while&#44; &#38; then I shall always take</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>the liberty to <sic>adress</sic> you&#44; if you&#39;ll kind<lb/>ly permit me.</p>
				<p>Expecting a reply to this&#44; at your earliest<lb/> convenience I remain reverend Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)">Your obedient servant</p>
			<p rend="indent(8)"><persName role="author">J. R. Hershom<add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
		</body>
